history.content: It won't be marked late, but you better change it ASAP in case professors have already pulled the responses.

Yes, there is a time stamp.

Faculty and hiring staff don't pay much attention to this, it's much more important that we get a qualified candidate. For the courses I hire for, I don't look at or care about the submission date at all.

IMO there is not harm in resubmitting. Some faculty will have already received their GSI applications and likely won't see your updates, but for Reading, tutoring, etc, it's worth it

children.subject: I would like to revise the preferences for the class I would like to tutor for next semester, if possible. Would it be too late to update my application at this time?

history.content:
First of all, do these applications have some sort of timestamp indicating when they have been submitted? In other words, do the people who review the applications know when a certain application has been submitted?

I'm thinking about revising my application a bit and submitting again, but I am worried that my application will be marked as having been submitted this late, even when I submitted earlier.  Am I then better off not revising my application?

(I checked @49, but it didn't really answer this question.)
